explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: This is the predicate that controls whether the if-block is executed. You must inspect its implementation/semantics to determine if the branch (the whole block) can ever be taken — otherwise that block would be unreachable.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; its behavior may influence whether GetById can succeed (e.g. initialization that can fail), so it is required to establish reachability of the if-block.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Used by OS_ObjectIdGetById to validate/convert object IDs; its validation logic determines whether a given task_id can produce OS_SUCCESS, affecting reachability.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Produces/validates the token returned by GetById; its logic affects whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can return success and thus whether the block is reachable.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Part of GetById failure paths/cleanup; understanding its use helps determine whether success paths exist or all paths always fail (making the if-block unreachable).
- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: Produces the task_id passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById. To decide if the if-condition can be true you must know what IDs this function can return (valid ranges/formats).
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return value compared against the result of OS_ObjectIdGetById. You need its definition/semantics to interpret return codes correctly.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL: The lock mode argument passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById can change its behaviour; its definition/semantics are needed to model GetById outcome.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The object-type argument passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById influences lookup/validation; its value/meaning is required to determine whether the lookup can succeed for the returned task_id.
- OS_TaskExit_Impl: The comment states this implementation never returns. You must inspect/confirm whether it is indeed a noreturn function (or can return), since that affects whether any code after its call would be reachable.

These symbols are the minimal set required to determine whether the if-block in OS_TaskExit can ever execute (i.e. is reachable) and to confirm non-return behavior of the final call. Additional callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById are included because they directly determine the success/failure outcome used in the conditional.
